sent to the notorious Auschwitz-Birkenau concentration camp in German-occupied Poland, where they would fight for their survival in a traumatic ordeal of unimaginable horror. Liberation in February 1945 should have meant the end of their nightmare, yet their homecoming would be delayed by widespread confusion as the Russians swept through Eastern Europe crushing the Nazi regime. After internment in numerous Russian camps and an uncertain future, Teréz and Ezri finally returned to their shattered hometown of Oradea in August 1945. Staying Human Through the Holocaust, originally titled Beverzett kotáblak ("Shattered Tablets"), was published in Hungarian in 1993 and in Romanian in 1995. Told in a direct and riveting style that will haunt the reader long after the story is over, this memoir is a glimpse of the darkest and most uplifting aspects of our humanity from both an individual and historical point of view.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945)zRomaniazOradeavPersonal narratives. 0aJewsxPersecutionszRomaniazOradea. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / Jewish.2bisacsh1 aDemarcisco, Audrey, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHercz, Anna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aHercz, Oren, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aWise, Maureen, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781552384565?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781552384565423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781552384565/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Com